1
00:00:01,790 --> 00:00:05,010
If you come to an
online shopping website

2
00:00:05,010 --> 00:00:07,335
and you're looking
at a specific item,

3
00:00:07,335 --> 00:00:09,405
say maybe a specific book,

4
00:00:09,405 --> 00:00:11,865
the website may show
you things like,

5
00:00:11,865 --> 00:00:13,620
"Here are some other
books similar to this

6
00:00:13,620 --> 00:00:16,605
one" or if you're browsing
a specific movie,

7
00:00:16,605 --> 00:00:17,940
it may say, "Here are

8
00:00:17,940 --> 00:00:19,890
some other movies
similar to this one."

9
00:00:19,890 --> 00:00:21,795
How do the websites do that?,

10
00:00:21,795 --> 00:00:23,550
so that when you're
looking at one item,

11
00:00:23,550 --> 00:00:26,790
it gives you other similar or
related items to consider.

12
00:00:26,790 --> 00:00:28,650
It turns out the collaborative

13
00:00:28,650 --> 00:00:30,240
filtering algorithm
that we've been talking

14
00:00:30,240 --> 00:00:32,550
about gives you a nice way to

15
00:00:32,550 --> 00:00:35,140
find related items.
Let's take a look.

16
00:00:35,140 --> 00:00:39,010
As part of the collaborative
filtering we've discussed,

17
00:00:39,010 --> 00:00:42,890
you learned features
x^(i) for every item i,

18
00:00:42,890 --> 00:00:44,750
for every movie i
or other type of

19
00:00:44,750 --> 00:00:47,125
item they're
recommending to users.

20
00:00:47,125 --> 00:00:48,665
Whereas early this week,

21
00:00:48,665 --> 00:00:52,550
I had used a hypothetical
example of the features

22
00:00:52,550 --> 00:00:54,740
representing how much a movie

23
00:00:54,740 --> 00:00:57,545
is a romance movie
versus an action movie.

24
00:00:57,545 --> 00:00:59,780
In practice, when you
use this algorithm to

25
00:00:59,780 --> 00:01:02,465
learn the features
x^(i) automatically,

26
00:01:02,465 --> 00:01:05,780
looking at the
individual features x_1,

27
00:01:05,780 --> 00:01:07,760
x_2, x_3,

28
00:01:07,760 --> 00:01:10,330
you find them to be
quite hard to interpret.

29
00:01:10,330 --> 00:01:13,205
Is quite hard to learn
features and say,

30
00:01:13,205 --> 00:01:15,800
x_1 is an action movie

31
00:01:15,800 --> 00:01:19,610
and x_2 is as a foreign
film and so on.

32
00:01:19,610 --> 00:01:22,925
But nonetheless, these
learned features,

33
00:01:22,925 --> 00:01:26,570
collectively x_1, x_2, x_3,

34
00:01:26,570 --> 00:01:28,265
other many features,

35
00:01:28,265 --> 00:01:31,940
and you have collectively
these features

36
00:01:31,940 --> 00:01:36,755
do convey something about
what that movie is like.

37
00:01:36,755 --> 00:01:41,570
It turns out that given
features x^(i) of item i,

38
00:01:41,570 --> 00:01:43,925
if you want to find other items,

39
00:01:43,925 --> 00:01:47,435
say other movies
related to movie i,

40
00:01:47,435 --> 00:01:51,755
then what you can do is try
to find the item k with

41
00:01:51,755 --> 00:01:58,110
features x^(k) that
is similar to x^(i).

42
00:01:58,110 --> 00:02:03,110
In particular, given a
feature vector x^(k),

43
00:02:03,110 --> 00:02:05,270
the way we determine
what are known as

44
00:02:05,270 --> 00:02:07,550
similar to the feature x^(i) is

45
00:02:07,550 --> 00:02:11,315
as follows: is the sum from
l equals 1 through n with

46
00:02:11,315 --> 00:02:16,370
n features of x^(k)_l
minus x^(i)_l square.

47
00:02:16,370 --> 00:02:19,715
This turns out to be the
squared distance between

48
00:02:19,715 --> 00:02:23,915
x^(k) and x^(i) and in math,

49
00:02:23,915 --> 00:02:28,220
this squared distance
between these two vectors,

50
00:02:28,220 --> 00:02:29,840
x^(k) and x^(i),

51
00:02:29,840 --> 00:02:32,570
is sometimes written
as follows as well.

52
00:02:32,570 --> 00:02:36,230
If you find not just
the one movie with

53
00:02:36,230 --> 00:02:38,465
the smallest distance between

54
00:02:38,465 --> 00:02:40,935
x^(k) and x^(i) but find say,

55
00:02:40,935 --> 00:02:43,430
the five or 10 items with

56
00:02:43,430 --> 00:02:45,845
the most similar
feature vectors,

57
00:02:45,845 --> 00:02:47,135
then you end up finding

58
00:02:47,135 --> 00:02:51,610
five or 10 related items
to the item x^(i).

59
00:02:51,610 --> 00:02:54,710
If you're building a website
and want to help users find

60
00:02:54,710 --> 00:02:56,180
related products to

61
00:02:56,180 --> 00:02:57,920
a specific product
they are looking at,

62
00:02:57,920 --> 00:03:01,430
this would be a nice
way to do so because

63
00:03:01,430 --> 00:03:07,125
the features x^(i) give a
sense of what item i is about,

64
00:03:07,125 --> 00:03:08,950
other items x^(k) with

65
00:03:08,950 --> 00:03:12,950
similar features will turn
out to be similar to item i.

66
00:03:12,950 --> 00:03:15,005
It turns out later this week,

67
00:03:15,005 --> 00:03:16,430
this idea of finding

68
00:03:16,430 --> 00:03:19,580
related items will be a small
building blocks that we'll

69
00:03:19,580 --> 00:03:20,855
use to get to

70
00:03:20,855 --> 00:03:24,470
an even more powerful
recommended system as well.

71
00:03:24,470 --> 00:03:26,780
Before wrapping up this section,

72
00:03:26,780 --> 00:03:28,280
I want to mention

73
00:03:28,280 --> 00:03:31,840
a few limitations of
collaborative filtering.

74
00:03:31,840 --> 00:03:33,590
In collaborative filtering, you

75
00:03:33,590 --> 00:03:35,270
have a set of items and so

76
00:03:35,270 --> 00:03:39,095
the users and the users have
rated some subset of items.

77
00:03:39,095 --> 00:03:41,810
One of this
weaknesses is that is

78
00:03:41,810 --> 00:03:44,690
not very good at the
cold start problem.

79
00:03:44,690 --> 00:03:48,050
For example, if there's a
new item in your catalog,

80
00:03:48,050 --> 00:03:50,360
say someone's just
published a new movie

81
00:03:50,360 --> 00:03:53,195
and hardly anyone has
rated that movie yet,

82
00:03:53,195 --> 00:03:55,610
how do you rank the new item

83
00:03:55,610 --> 00:03:58,780
if very few users
have rated it before?

84
00:03:58,780 --> 00:04:01,640
Similarly, for new users

85
00:04:01,640 --> 00:04:04,145
that have rated
only a few items,

86
00:04:04,145 --> 00:04:07,795
how can we make sure we show
them something reasonable?

87
00:04:07,795 --> 00:04:10,155
We could see in
an earlier video,

88
00:04:10,155 --> 00:04:12,500
how mean normalization can help

89
00:04:12,500 --> 00:04:15,110
with this and it
does help a lot.

90
00:04:15,110 --> 00:04:17,480
But perhaps even better ways to

91
00:04:17,480 --> 00:04:20,465
show users that rated
very few items,

92
00:04:20,465 --> 00:04:22,970
things that are likely
to interest them.

93
00:04:22,970 --> 00:04:26,089
This is called the
cold start problem,

94
00:04:26,089 --> 00:04:28,835
because when you
have a new item,

95
00:04:28,835 --> 00:04:30,515
there are few users have rated,

96
00:04:30,515 --> 00:04:35,105
or we have a new user that's
rated very few items,

97
00:04:35,105 --> 00:04:38,000
the results of collaborative
filtering for that item

98
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:40,895
or for that user may
not be very accurate.

99
00:04:40,895 --> 00:04:42,230
The second limitation of

100
00:04:42,230 --> 00:04:44,660
collaborative filtering
is it doesn't give you

101
00:04:44,660 --> 00:04:47,185
a natural way to use
side information

102
00:04:47,185 --> 00:04:50,190
or additional information
about items or users.

103
00:04:50,190 --> 00:04:53,989
For example, for a given
movie in your catalog,

104
00:04:53,989 --> 00:04:56,510
you might know what is
the genre of the movie,

105
00:04:56,510 --> 00:04:57,980
who had a movie stars,

106
00:04:57,980 --> 00:04:59,150
whether it is a studio,

107
00:04:59,150 --> 00:05:01,310
what is the budget, and so on.

108
00:05:01,310 --> 00:05:04,780
You may have a lot of
features about a given movie.

109
00:05:04,780 --> 00:05:06,515
For a single user,

110
00:05:06,515 --> 00:05:09,185
you may know something
about their demographics,

111
00:05:09,185 --> 00:05:12,110
such as their age,
gender, location.

112
00:05:12,110 --> 00:05:15,200
They express preferences,
such as if they tell

113
00:05:15,200 --> 00:05:17,330
you they like certain
movies genres

114
00:05:17,330 --> 00:05:19,330
but not other movies genres,

115
00:05:19,330 --> 00:05:22,970
or it turns out if you know
the user's IP address,

116
00:05:22,970 --> 00:05:26,050
that can tell you a lot
about a user's location,

117
00:05:26,050 --> 00:05:29,060
and knowing the user's
location might also help

118
00:05:29,060 --> 00:05:32,200
you guess what might the
user be interested in,

119
00:05:32,200 --> 00:05:35,180
or if you know whether
the user is accessing

120
00:05:35,180 --> 00:05:39,140
your site on a mobile
or on a desktop,

121
00:05:39,140 --> 00:05:41,510
or if you know what web
browser they're using.

122
00:05:41,510 --> 00:05:44,090
It turns out all of these
are little cues you can get.

123
00:05:44,090 --> 00:05:45,320
They can be surprisingly

124
00:05:45,320 --> 00:05:48,305
correlated with the
preferences of a user.

125
00:05:48,305 --> 00:05:51,200
It turns out by the way,
that it is known that users,

126
00:05:51,200 --> 00:05:53,780
that use the Chrome
versus Firefox versus

127
00:05:53,780 --> 00:05:56,495
Safari versus the
Microsoft Edge browser,

128
00:05:56,495 --> 00:05:58,595
they actually behave in
very different ways.

129
00:05:58,595 --> 00:06:01,820
Even knowing the user
web browser can give you

130
00:06:01,820 --> 00:06:03,170
a hint when you have collected

131
00:06:03,170 --> 00:06:06,235
enough data of what this
particular user may like.

132
00:06:06,235 --> 00:06:08,795
Even though
collaborative filtering,

133
00:06:08,795 --> 00:06:10,700
we have multiple users give

134
00:06:10,700 --> 00:06:12,695
you ratings of multiple items,

135
00:06:12,695 --> 00:06:14,740
is a very powerful
set of algorithms,

136
00:06:14,740 --> 00:06:16,900
it also has some limitations.

137
00:06:16,900 --> 00:06:18,330
In the next video,

138
00:06:18,330 --> 00:06:19,490
let's go on to

139
00:06:19,490 --> 00:06:21,920
develop content-based
filtering algorithms,

140
00:06:21,920 --> 00:06:24,835
which can address a lot
of these limitations.

141
00:06:24,835 --> 00:06:26,900
Content-based filtering
algorithms are

142
00:06:26,900 --> 00:06:28,820
a steady art technique used in

143
00:06:28,820 --> 00:06:30,950
many commercial
applications today.

144
00:06:30,950 --> 00:06:33,810
Let's go take a look
